{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/use-python-to-automate-your-excel-work-c16b6e5ab58e", "time": 1683014162.966223, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/use-python-to-automate-your-excel-work-c16b6e5ab58e/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Use Python to Automate Your Excel Work! | by Nik Piepenbreier | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Use Python to Automate Your Excel Work!", "description": "Chances are, you can\u2019t escape Excel (and it\u2019s probably good you don\u2019t entirely!). Learning how to make working with the application easier and how to automate repetitive tasks, is an important skill\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLYt6YwKmonu0x8oI_tLT_vaOFzRU64ptK", "anchor_text": "Pandas introductory series on YouTube", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://github.com/datagy/mediumdata/raw/master/exceltopandas.xlsx", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCm7fT9_IdCDbeBXjAwL9IIg?view_as=subscriber", "anchor_text": "YouTube", "paragraph_index": 20}], "all_paragraphs": ["In this post, you\u2019ll learn how to automate some of your common, tedious Excel tasks.", "Chances are, you can\u2019t escape Excel (and it\u2019s probably good you don\u2019t entirely!). Learning how to make working with the application easier and how to automate repetitive tasks, is an important skill!", "Over the next few minutes, you\u2019ll learn how to combine data from multiple sheets, create summary statistics based on that data, and create helpful visualizations. All in a few lines of code!", "Let\u2019s begin by importing the Pandas library. If you\u2019re not familiar with the library, check out my Pandas introductory series on YouTube!", "I have created a file for this tutorial that includes three sheets, covering data from three different months. You can download the file here, or use the URL to import the file directly into a Pandas dataframe.", "In this first bit of code, you\u2019ve imported the Pandas library (and assigned it the alias pd). You then assigned the Excel file to an ExcelFile object. Finally, you printed out the sheet names of all the sheets in the file, but using the .sheet_names attribute.", "Now that you know what sheets are contained in the file, let\u2019s actually create a dataframe of all the data.", "The big benefit of using this approach, rather than listing out the sheet names, is that as months are added to your file, the list won\u2019t need to be modified!", "Let\u2019s first create a dataframe object and add in the additional data files.", "In the code above, you first created an empty dataframe object. Then you used a for-loop to loop over each sheet in the Excel workbook, generated a temporary dataframe with its data (skipping the first three rows), and appended each item to the dataframe df. Finally, you printed the first five records, using the .head()method.", "Alternatively, if you wanted to combine the data in a single line, you could write the following code, which uses the Pandas .concat()function:", "Now that you\u2019ve combined the data, let\u2019s run some analysis on this.", "Let\u2019s say, you\u2019ve been asked to look at the total value of each sale by Type and Region, across the various months.", "We can do this using the Pandas `.pivot_table()` function, which I\u2019ve covered extensively in this YouTube video:", "Let\u2019s create a Pandas pivot table:", "Above, you\u2019ve created a pivot table that has two indices (the month and the Type). The month is generated using the Pandas .dtaccessor, which returns the month as an integer, where 1 is equal to January. The columns are made up Region.", "Finally, let\u2019s create some visualizations of this data.", "Perhaps you\u2019ll want to create a graph that shows the data represented as stacked columns.", "Let\u2019s use the matplotlib integration in Pandas to generate this chart:", "In this post, you learned how to create a Pandas dataframe from data across multiple Excel worksheets. You learned how to quickly analyze your data and create a visualization of your data.", "Check out some of my other posts or subscribe to me on YouTube for frequent tips!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fc16b6e5ab58e&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fuse-python-to-automate-your-excel-work-c16b6e5ab58e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fuse-python-to-automate-your-excel-work-c16b6e5ab58e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fuse-python-to-automate-your-excel-work-c16b6e5ab58e&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fuse-python-to-automate-your-excel-work-c16b6e5ab58e&source=